column49: I am not happy with the push to digital flyers. I teach preschool and the kids like to turn the pages of the flyers and  pick out their books.   I have seen a sharp decline  in orders since you stopped sending physical flyers. Also I should be able to set the due date that orders are due.  I teach in a private preschool, we use our November order to order books as Christmas presents for our students.  I need to be able to submit the order early enough in the month to ensure shipping in time to have them ready before Christmas break. You listing a different order deadline then what I post is confusing to parents. I used to love scholastic book clubs. But between your drastic rise in prices and the changes you have made recently, I’m not sure it’s a good fit for our school any longer.

column49: I am a long-time customer of Scholastic as an educator for over 40 years and now as a grandparent. I have also worked Scholastic bookfairs at schools. I understand the need to raise book prices but the selection of books from the book clubs and at the fairs is far less than in previous years including just last year. At the recent bookfair at my granddaughter's school, there were many hardcover books offered but not purchased. In addition there were many fur covered journals and organizers that also did not sell.  There were very few books for kids who brought $5 or $10 to the fair. Parents are struggling to make ends meet and it is disappointing to send kids home without a book when they brought too little money. I am hoping this is a temporary change. Please consider sending more cool deal/special low price books to the fairs and cut down on the hardcover books which are not affordable for most kids.

column49: Ive been a loyal scholastic teacher over the last nine years.  I teach third grade and  have always had large orders from my classes.  This year, I have been struggling  and haven't had one order placed.  I send home the flyers and also promote it in my weekly newsletters.  The only change I have noticed is that the flyers have changed to 2nd/3rd grade combined.  Perhaps this is putting some third grade parents off that it is geared to second as well.  Any chance Scholastic might consider switching back to a 3rd grade flyer only.   Thank you!

column49: I like that you can select a flyer and select books from the flyer instead of entering the item number.  But after I added a book to my cart and selected Continue Shopping, I expected to return to the flyer I was shopping in.  I had to select the flyer again. column49: The website seems to have gone through some major changes in the past year, and unfortunately not for the better:  1) Why is the Family Order Due Date predetermined? In the past, I used to be able to set the date for ordering and print letters to send home with flyers, but now not anymore. The date is already set. This is VERY inconvenient and will likely lead to LESS orders from me and my families.  2) Also, there used to be a Dollar Store available (book that are $1) but I no longer see that available.   I've been a Scholastic Book Clubs members for many many years, and this is the first time I've been a bit disappointed and frustrated by the changes. I hope some of these features will return soon.

column49: I realize there have been changes at Scholastic and with a new look on the catalogs, but  I am disappointed.  I feel the titles are not quality books like when I first started teaching over 20 years ago. I thought I'd see how the new look goes and give it a try. I'm disappointed that the holiday catalog was more junky stuff than books. I am also saddened that for Christmas you have many secular Christmas books, 1 Kwannza and 1 Hannukah, but no Christian books about Christmas.     I was also looking for the teacher packs, so I can purchase books for my class for Christmas presents and I couldn't find any. The packs were a great price point for this teacher who had many students and not much money to spend. I prefer to purchase a holiday book or hopefully a Christian book for my students, but I do not see that availability this year at my price point.  I enjoy giving parents the book catalogs as I am a book nerd and want my first graders reading, but I  may stop sending them home. loyalc

column49: The new policies regarding due dates are extremely frustrating. Whenever I have spoken to someone about it, I am not listened to and just told this is how it is going to be without any flexibility. Teachers should be able to set THIER OWN due dates. Then...if it is to be automatically submitted after, the teacher has some control over when they want to send them home and how to maximize their rewards. As it is, this takes away benefits from the teacher. I will be discontinuing using scholastic book clubs for my classroom, which is a shame since I have been supporting Scholastic for the past 10 years with my own classroom and through book orders for my own children 12 years prior to that. It would do the company some good to listen to their teachers since I am sure this is how a lot of business is brought to them.

column49: I used to love using Scholastic Book Clubs in my classroom, but I am NOT a fan of the new format.  I have stopped sending home the flyers and advertising the book club because the new flyers are filled with more toys and junk, rather than just books.  It also feels like most of the books included are either expensive or are box sets.  I work in a city school where most of my students can't afford to by $10 and $15 books and the new flyers have very minimal options at a lower price point.  Bring back the original Scholastics and you might bring back this teacher.  Until then, I'm really disappointed in what the Scholastic Book Clubs has become.
